node-legofy is a playful Node.js script that turns regular images into LEGO‑style
mosaics. Give it a picture and it recreates it as a grid of coloured bricks,
complete with options to tweak the output.

## What it does

- **Processes images on the command line**, reading an input file and writing
  out a transformed version.
- **Maps pixels to a LEGO‑like palette**, snapping colours to a limited set so
  the result feels like something you could actually build.
- **Supports configuration**, letting you adjust things like brick size and
  output dimensions.

It’s more toy than production tool, but it is surprisingly fun to run a few
favourite images through it and see how they translate into bricks.

## Why I built it

node-legofy started as a side project mixing two things I enjoy: image
processing experiments and LEGO. It was a good excuse to play with Node.js
scripts, buffers and colour maths, and it turned into a small utility that
people still occasionally pick up for creative projects.

The repository includes examples, benchmarks and usage instructions if you want
to legofy your own images.

